time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T18:35:24.679Z\">6.35pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Over on the <strong>Spectator</strong>'s Coffee House <a href=\"http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/coffeehouse/2013/10/energy-bosses-boost-tory-tortoise-in-energy-row-with-green-taxes-pledge/\">blog</a>, <strong>Isabel Hardman</strong> sounds underwhelmed by MPs' performance in taking on the energy bosses: &quot;the energy companies have hardly had the grilling they were expecting: more of a gentle warming.&quot;</p> <p>She writes that&nbsp;the person who has done the most to make the big six witnesses uncomfortable is one of the other witnesses: Stephen Fitzpatrick, the managing director of Ovo Energy.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>He took apart those sitting next to him in the Thatcher Room, saying that Ovo couldn’t see the prices on the wholesale market that would lead to the sort of rises that the Big Six have been announcing recently.&nbsp;</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>John Rentoul</strong> at the<strong> Independent</strong> also thinks that the MPs failed to inflict &quot;<a href=\"http://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/the-big-six-in-front-of-mps-this-was-supposed-to-be-a-grilling-but-even-russell-brand-would-have-struggled-to-give-one-8911552.html\">ritual cathartic humiliation</a>&quot;.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Normal people don’t have to sit through select committee meetings, but I suspect that most of us have an understanding of market economics that works at two levels. Level one is that prices seem to go up a lot, don’t seem to go down when world prices go down, and that the bosses of a lot of companies seem to get paid an awful lot, which doesn’t seem to go down if their companies do badly. But level two is that nationalising the energy industry would not make gas and electricity bills magically cheaper.</p> </blockquote> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T18:45:39.236Z\">at 6.45pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526ffa97e4b08c7e086ff154\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T18:26:54.237Z\">6.26pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Still waiting for MPs to return to the Thatcher room to wrap up this session on the 'big six' with Ofgem's chief executive.</p> <p>So time for a quick backgrounder: earlier this year the committee accused Ofgem of failing to improve transparency in the energy market. Ofgem hired BDO accountancy firm to advise on financial reporting of energy companies, but then failed to take up its recommendations, arguing they would put unnecessary burdens on the big six.</p> <p>MPs rejected this argument in their <a href=\"http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmselect/cmenergy/108/10802.htm\">report on energy prices, profits and poverty</a>:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>We believe that taken as a whole, the benefits of BDOs recommendations - in terms of improvements to transparency and comparability of the statements and associated improvements in consumer trust - significantly outweigh any burdens on the six largest vertically integrated energy companies.&nbsp;</p> <p>We recommend that Ofgem should require the six largest vertically integrated companies to implement BDO' recommendations 1 (publishing statements to the same year-end), 2 (independent auditor opinion on statements), and 4(reporting of trading function results). We also encourage Ofgem to consider requiring implementation of BDO's recommendations in full and to publish, in its response to this report, its analysis of the cost to energy companies of full implementation.&nbsp;</p> </blockquote> <p>With MPs calling Ofgem &quot;a paper tiger&quot;, it is not only the big six energy bosses that are attempting to defend their reputations today.&nbsp;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526ff809e4b0ded76c0a9112\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T18:02:00.671Z\">6.02pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The division bell is ringing again. Short break while MPs go off to vote.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526ff71ce4b0ffc73763b662\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T18:01:41.986Z\">6.01pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Alan Whitehead is asking about the BDO recommendations (see<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/29/business-blog-india-raises-interest-rates-to-tackle-inflation-live#block-526fdd0ae4b01566f5a3942e\"> 4.08</a> for background).</p> <p>Wright says Ofgem has committed to looking again at those recommendations and will be coming out with a call for evidence and &quot;engaging with stakeholders&quot;.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>We have led the way in improving transparency in this market.. without the actions we took this debate would not be possible.</p> </blockquote> <p>This should be seen as Ofgem's defence, after the same group of MPs criticised the regulator for dismissing the BDO report, a series of recommendations to improve transparency.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526ff642e4b0ffc73763b660\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:56:51.764Z\">5.56pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>One MP thinks a different energy market model could work better: why not have &quot;fierce competition&quot; in generating electricity, but have co-operatively owned business model to supply consumers.</p> <p>Wright says there are many different models of running energy systems throughout the world. &quot;It is the government's policy to have a competitive market in the supply of retail and gas.&quot;</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <ti