e3d04f292fcb-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"US retail sales fell 0.1% in September.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>US retail sales fell 0.1% in September. Photograph: Robert Harding World Imagery/A/Alamy</figcaption> </figure> <p>Weak car sales were a drag in September, pushing overall <a href=\"http://www.census.gov/retail/\">retail sales down 0.1%</a> on a monthly basis. It wasn't far off economists' prediction of flat sales.</p> <p>Excluding cars, retail sales actually rose by a 0.4%, and sales were 3.2% higher compared with September 2012.</p> <p>Economists said it was difficult to get too excited about the numbers because they related to the period before the US government shutdown.&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>James Knightley</strong> of ING said:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>We have to remember that this was a pre-government shutdown figure and so its usefulness as a guide for Federal Reserve policy is limited.</p> </blockquote> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T13:49:39.795Z\">at 1.49pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526fad54e4b08c7e086ff130\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T12:50:32.104Z\">12.50pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">European shares - lunchtime round-up</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Europe's major indices are still higher.</p> <p><strong>FTSE 100</strong>: +0.61% at 6,766.38</p> <p><strong>CAC 40</strong>: +0.5% at 4,272.78</p> <p><strong>DAX 30</strong>: +0.18% at 8,995.09</p> <p><strong>IBEX</strong>: +1.11% at 9,844.6</p> <p><strong>FTSE MIB</strong>: +1.75% at 19,158</p> <p>London traders returned to their desks today after Britain's <a href=\"http://www.guprod.gnl/uk-news/2013/oct/29/storm-death-destruction-return-to-work\">worst storm in a decade</a>. While travel was severely disrupted and hundreds of thosands of homes lost power, economics editor <strong>Larry Elliot</strong> believes the economic impact will be limted.</p> <p>He <a href=\"http://www.guprod.gnl/business/economics-blog/2013/oct/28/storm-battered-britain-not-economy-bad-weather\">argues</a>:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>There are good reasons for expecting Britain's growth rate to slow down as 2013 draws to a close but the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/oct/28/britain-storm-winds-death-flooding\">storm that has battered the south of England </a>is not one of them.</p> <p>To be sure, a complete shutdown of the country would have an impact on national output, as was illustrated by the blizzards in December 2010.</p> <p>They had a material impact on gross domestic product in the fourth quarter of that year because the disruption was widespread and protracted.</p> <p>But that's not going to be the case this time. Firstly, the storm passed quickly and the Met Office gave plenty of warning that the bad <a href=\"http://www.guprod.gnl/uk/weather\">weather</a> was coming so people planned to work from home. Secondly, many workers were off anyway because of school half-term holidays. Thirdly, many of those who had an unexpected day off will have spent money in shops and restaurants. Finally, the fact that the bad weather came in October – the first month of the fourth quarter of 2013 – means there will be plenty of time to make up for lost output.</p> <p>There will have been some loss of output as a result of the bad weather, but at the most it will have shaved 0.1 points off GDP in the fourth quarter, and probably less than that.</p> </blockquote> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T12:58:34.652Z\">at 12.58pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526fac59e4b0ffc73763b627\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T12:42:38.366Z\">12.42pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">More on UK mortgages...</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Katie Allen</strong>, the Guardian's economics reporter, tells how the biggest rise in UK mortgage approvals since February 2008 is &quot;fanning fears&quot; of a fresh housing market bubble:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/mortgages\">Mortgages</a> approved by British lenders jumped to their highest level for more than five years in September, fanning fears the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/housingmarket\">housing market</a> was already heating up even before the latest government support kicked in.</p> <p>Banks, building societies and other lenders <a href=\"http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/statistics/documents/mc/2013/sep/tablesa-n.xlsx\">approved 66,735 mortgages in September</a>, the biggest monthly total since February 2008, before the global financial crisis took hold.</p> <p>The figures, from the <a href=\"http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/statistics/Pages/mc/2013/sep/default.aspx\">Bank of England</a>, were just ahead of City forecasts for 66,000 and compared with an upwardly revised 63,396 in August. Mortgage approvals are seen by economists as a good early indicator of where the housing market is headed.</p> <p>They follow government data on Monday showing <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/28/house-prices-rise-england-land-registry-bubble\">house prices rose in every English region in September</a> and are likely to be seized on by those who argue that the government's <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/help-to-buy-scheme\">Help to Buy scheme</a> risks creating a new bubble.</p> </blockquote> <p>Read the full story <strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/29/mortgage-approvals-february-2008-help-to-buy\">here</a></strong>.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526f9d5ce4b08c7e086ff12f\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T11:48:38.194Z\">11.48am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Ireland gets a final visit from Troika of international lenders</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-f7f32f83-cc24-4f43-9c8e-9c09f015366d\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/2/29/1330519545721/An-Irish-flag-flies-next--008.jpg\" alt=\"Ireland to receive a final visit from the Troika of international lenders.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Ireland to receive a final visit from the Troika of international lenders. Photograph: Francois Lenoir/Reuters</figcaption> </figure> <p>Lenders from the International Monetary Fund, European Union, and European Central Bank - the so-called <strong>Troika</strong> - will pay a final visit to Dublin today.</p> <p>It follows the bailout which Ireland was forced into following the near collapse of its banking system at the height of the financial crisis. The country is hoping to become the first to exit the rescue programme.</p> <p>This from our Ireland correspondent <strong>Henry McDonald</strong>, in Dublin:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Officials from the International Monetary Fund, the EU and the European Bank will make their 12th and final visit to the Irish capital today to review the Republic's economy as heads towards exiting the bail out.</p> <p>The so-called Troika will examine the progress Ireland is making towards driving down its national debt and moving to restoring economic sovereignty.</p> <p>Ireland will become the first country in the EU to leave the bail out programme.</p> <p>The Republic was forced to borrow 67.5bn euros (&pound;57.4bn) after its biggest banks almost collapsed in November 2010.</p> <p>However, the state's debt-to-GDP ratio is still around 120% and Irish banks have yet to properly deal with the tens of thousands of its customers in mortgage arrears. Meanwhile, unemployment remains more than 14 per cent of the workforce.</p> </blockquote> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T11:54:24.463Z\">at 11.54am GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526f99a1e4b08c7e086ff12e\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T11:25:09.331Z\">11.25am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Former Co-op bosses grilled by MPs</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Our City Editor <strong>Jill Treanor</strong> is following the session live and tweeting <strong><a href=\"https://twitter.com/jilltreanor\">here</a></strong>.</p> <p><strong>Barry Tootell</strong>, former chief executive of the bank, has told MPs that the downgrade to junk status by Moody's in May was more severe than expected. He has also denied misleading the market about the state of the bank.</p> <p>See <strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/27/co-operative-group-retail?CMP=twt_gu\">here</a></strong> for a great read on the Co-op fiasco.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/jilltreanor/statuses/395155911557148672\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Barry Tootell says it was his recommendation that the Verde deal - the Lloyds branches - should not proceed</p>— Jill Treanor (@jilltreanor) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/jilltreanor/statuses/395155911557148672\">October 29, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T11:58:43.766Z\">at 11.58am GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526f943ce4b08c7e086ff12c\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T11:09:06.244Z\">11.09am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Spanish retail sales rise for the first time in more than three years</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Turning to Spain, retail sales rose by 2.2% in September compared with the same month a year earlier. It followed a 4.8% drop in August according to official figures, and marked the first annual rise in more than three years.</p> <p><strong>Chris Williamson</strong>, chief economist at <strong>Markit</strong>, puts the rise into context on Twitter:</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/WilliamsonChris/statuses/395133254967119873\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Retail sales in <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Spain&amp;src=hash\">#Spain</a> charted: 1st annual rise (+2.2%) since Jun'10. Have been only 4 +ve y/y sales months since2007 <a href=\"http://t.co/raflkzAMp2\">pic.twitter.com/raflkzAMp2</a></p>— Chris Williamson (@WilliamsonChris) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/WilliamsonChris/statuses/395133254967119873\">October 29, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526f8b1fe4b0ffc73763b61b\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T10:28:50.248Z\">10.28am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">UK mortgage approvals highest in more than five and a half years</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-d02bef88-7bfb-420e-946f-8926aa7f1cff\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Money/Pix/pictures/2009/12/23/1261565871131/Mortgage-approvals-increa-001.jpg\" alt=\"Mortgage approvals increased by 5.3% in September\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Mortgage approvals increased by 5.3% in September to the highest level in more than five and a half years. Photograph: Russell Boyce/Reuters</figcaption> </figure> <p><strong>UK mortgage approvals</strong> for house purchases (i.e. excluding remortgages) rose 5.3% to 66,735 in September, from 63,396 in August.</p> <p>It was the highest level since February 2008, before the global financial crisis intensified in September that year with the collapse of US investment bank <strong>Lehman Brothers</strong>.</p> <p>The <strong>Bank of England</strong> data will be taken as a further sign that Britain's housing market was warming up even before the second phase of the government's <strong>Help to Buy</strong> scheme was introduced earlier this month. However, mortgage approvals are still below pre-crisis levels, with monthly approvals averaging above 100,000 in 2006 and 2007.</p> <p><strong>Howard Archer</strong>, chief UK economist at<strong> IHS Global Insight</strong>, had this to say on the Bank's data:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The marked increase in mortgage approvals in September provides compelling evidence that housing market activity was already gaining appreciable momentum even before the Help to Buy mortgage guarantee scheme came into being in early October.</p> <p>While the strength of house price rises in London is becoming an increasing concern and pushing up the overall national increase in house prices, we are currently a long way off from an overall housing market bubble emerging.</p> <p>Nevertheless, there is a mounting danger that house prices could really take off over the coming months, especially ifalready significantly improving housing market activity and rising buyer interest is lifted appreciably further by the Help to Buy mortgage guarantee scheme</p> <p>It is therefore of vital importance that policymakers closely monitor the situation and are prepared to act quickly and decisively if signs of the housing market overheating become increasingly widespread and pronounced.</p> </blockquote> <p>The <strong>Bank of England</strong> also revealed that lending to non-financial companies&nbsp;rose by &pound;720m in September., following a &pound;3.7m fall in August.</p> <p>However, while lending to large companies increased by &pound;1.1bn, loans to small and medium-sized enterprises fell by &pound;383m. </p> <p><strong>Adam Marshall,</strong> director of policy and external affairs at the<strong> British Chambers of Commerce</strong>, said more help was needed for SMEs:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>It’s good to see overall business lending rise, as this has an impact on business confidence. Yet these new figures show that while large firms have little difficulty tapping debt markets, SMEs – and particular young, fast-growing firms – continue to struggle to access growth capital.</p> <p>Both policy-makers and financial institutions need to do more to help fast-growing SMEs access finance. The British Business Bank has a huge role to play here, and should be enhanced with additional capital to help plug the gap.</p> </blockquote> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T13:42:49.868Z\">at 1.42pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526f8169e4b0ffc73763b618\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T09:47:50.222Z\">9.47am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">European markets are up</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The major European markets are all slightly higher this morning:</p> <p><strong>FTSE 100</strong>: +0.36% at 6,749.05</p> <p><strong>CAC 40</strong>: +0.17% at 4,258.99</p> <p><strong>DAX 30</strong>: +0.07% at 8,985.04</p> <p><strong>IBEX</strong>: +0.55% at 9,789.2</p> <p><strong>FTSE MIB</strong>: +1.3% at 19,073.95</p> <p><strong>BP</strong> is the biggest riser on the <strong>FTSE 100</strong>, with shares up 5% at 475p.</p> <p>The company is flying high after a better than expected set of third-quarter results which included a dividend hike and a plegde to return proceeds of asset sales to shareholders. It plans to sell $10bn (&pound;6.2bn) of assets by the end of 2015. </p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T09:59:47.530Z\">at 9.59am GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526f77d6e4b0ded76c0a90d6\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T09:12:15.639Z\">9.12am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">MPs to grill Big Six energy providers</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-8cd33c77-6212-4bbf-aa33-003b6f1b8bb3\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/29/1383039260326/a2851f7c-9dfa-412e-a6a2-ae65deda565e-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Britain's Big Six energy providers will be grilled by MPs this afternoon on recent price rises.  EPA/ANDY RAIN\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Britain's Big Six energy providers will be grilled by MPs this afternoon on recent price rises. EPA/ANDY RAIN Photograph: ANDY RAIN/EPA</figcaption> </figure> <p>MPs on House of Commons select committees are in for a busy day. The main event starts at 2.30 in the Thatcher Room, Portcullis House, when the <strong>Big Six energy companies</strong> will be grilled on prices by the <strong>energy and climate change committee</strong>.</p> <p>I think they can expect some fairly robust questioning following the intense debate about rising UK energy bills. First we had Labour <strong>Ed Miliband</strong>, who pledged to freeze energy prices for 20 months should his party be elected at the next election.</p> <p>Then came the prices rises. Four of the Big Six - <strong>SSE</strong>, <strong>British Gas</strong>, <strong>npower</strong> and <strong>Scottish Power</strong> - moved in quick succession, with some customers facing price hikes of more than 10% just in time for winter.</p> <p>MPs will no doubt try to get to the bottom of what is really happening to wholesale energy prices, and how they affect household bills.</p> <p>As <strong>Rowena Mason</strong>, The Guardian's political correspondent, reports:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Some of Britain's big six energy companies have seen their wholesale electricity costs fall over the last three years while still putting up prices for millions of households.</p> <p>The figures will put yet more pressure on the firms to explain why bills and UK profits have been going up, as they appear before a influential House of Commons committee of MPs.</p> </blockquote> <p>Read the full story <strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/29/energy-firms-raised-prices-as-wholesale-costs-fall\">here</a></strong>.</p> <p>Other promising sessions today:</p> <p><strong>9.30am - </strong>Business, Innovation and Skills Committee takes evidence on the <strong>UK retail sector</strong> from witnesses including veteran retailer <strong>Bill Grimse</strong>y and business minister <strong>Michael Fallon</strong>.</p> <p><strong>10am</strong> - Treasury Committee takes evidence from former executives of the <strong>Co-operative Banking Group </strong>on the collapse of the deal to buy more than 600 Lloyds branches, know as Project Verde.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T09:43:22.594Z\">at 9.43am GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526f6bb4e4b0ffc73763b617\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T08:11:08.926Z\">8.11am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Britain's banks are the biggest fallers this morning</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Banks are not popular this morning. The <strong>FTSE 100</strong> has opened slightly higher, up 0.2% at 6,740, but <strong>UK banks</strong> are trading lower.</p> <p>Lloyds Banking Group: -3.3% at 77<br />Royal Bank of Scotland: -2% at 360.2<br />Standard Chartered: -1.8% at 1,506<br />Barclays: -1.1% at 260.4</p> <p><strong>Lloyds</strong> has this morning revealed a further &pound;750m hit for payment protection insurance, taking its total bill for the mis-selling scandal to more than &pound;8bn. The hit contributed to a &pound;440m loss in the third quarter.</p> <p>It was the first update from the bailed out bank since the government started sellling off part of its stake last month.</p> <p>There was some brighter news from Lloyds as chief executive <strong>Ant&oacute;nio Horta-Os&oacute;rio</strong> said it was in discussions to start resuming dividends, and increased his forecasts for margins.</p> <p>Read the full story from our City Editor <strong>Jill Treanor</strong> <strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/29/lloyds-loss-ppi-claims-rise-again\">here</a></strong>.</p> <p>Meanwhile <strong>UBS</strong> shares are down 6% after the Swiss bank was told by regulators that it must increase its capital reserves temporarily by 50% to deal with potential litigation and compliance issues.</p> <p>It dampens the bank's ability's to improve profitability, and hit shares despite a better than expected third-quarter net income of 577 million Swiss francs. Full story <strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/29/ubs-regulators-currency-investigations\">here</a></strong>.</p> <p>Shares in <strong>Deutsche Bank</strong> are down 2.5% after it reported a 94% fall in third quarter profit. It was below expectations and driven partly by a €1.2bn increase in litigation provisions.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/gfhay/statuses/395100064500027392\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Investors have well and truly turned their noses up at bank results today: UBS opens down 5.7%, Lloyds off 3.4%, Deutsche 2.5%.</p>— George Hay (@gfhay) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/gfhay/statuses/395100064500027392\">October 29, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T10:06:05.970Z\">at 10.06am GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526f68f7e4b0ffc73763b616\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T07:59:25.736Z\">7.59am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">India raises interest rates to 7.75%</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-a8531fab-c28a-4603-86f5-ec42a12319f6\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2013/8/19/1376934171154/The-Reserve-Bank-of-India-010.jpg\" alt=\"The Reserve Bank of India, Mumbai\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) in Mumbai. Photograph: Vivek Prakash/REUTERS</figcaption> </figure> <p><strong>Good morning, and welcome to our rolling coverage of events across the financial market, the global economy, the eurozone and the business world.</strong></p> <p>It's a busy day ahead both on the economics and corporate front in Europe and the US.</p> <p>Overnight India's central bank raised interest rates for a second consecutive month in an attempt to fight inflation and despite sluggish growth.</p> <p>The Reserve Bank of India raised its policy repo rate by 0.25 percentage points to 7.75%. Annual inflation in India rose to 9.84% in September from 9.52% in August. Growth slowed however in the second quarter, to 4.4% on an annual basis.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T11:18:13.803Z\">at 11.18am GMT</time></p> </div><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421179698|2013-11-05T11:03:55Z|6a82ac2d2c53173f5c514727657ea75dfddaf4b1 -->",
