      "id":"commentisfree/2013/oct/28/shambolic-energy-policy-competition-big-six",
      "sectionId":"commentisfree",
      "sectionName":"Comment is free",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-28T10:10:59Z",
      "webTitle":"Our shambolic energy policy needs more than just competition | Simon Jenkins",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/28/shambolic-energy-policy-competition-big-six",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/28/shambolic-energy-policy-competition-big-six",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<strong>Simon Jenkins: First thoughts:</strong> The government is right to try and break the big six oligopoly, but a deep audit is required if we are to aid the poor or the planet",
        "headline":"Our shambolic energy policy needs more than just competition",
        "body":"<p>Britain's energy policy is chaotic, lost in a morass of subsidies, regulations, lobbies and taboos. No one can understand it, which is why most retreat to slogans and prejudice. The revelation that <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/oct/26/british-gas-caroline-flint-credit-windfall\" title=\"\">British Gas treats my \"direct debit\" credit balance as a free loan</a> merely adds fury to my own contribution.</p><p>The government is proposing to give the statutory regulators \"more power to enforce competition\". The big six energy companies – who have ousted bankers as the top capitalist ogres thanks to their apparent profiteering – exploit the ebbs and flows of state intervention to push up prices at what seems an unjustified rate. Last week came the most extravagant intervention of all, with <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/21/nuclear-power-hinckley-deal-energy\" title=\"\">the Hinkley Point nuclear contract going to France</a>, and no scope for competition from small-scale nuclear generation.</p><p>Meanwhile the regulators are themselves at odds. The discredited energy policeman, Ofgem, is now to be overseen by the Office of Fair Trading, who are overseen in turn by ministers, who are themselves at odds with <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/25/ed-davey-green-levy-energy\" title=\"\">Liberal Democrats fighting for green taxes and Tories against them</a>. Both are cursed by the impossible pursuit of an arbitrary target to cut carbon emissions by a fixed date. This has degenerated into a shambles of carbon price manipulation and subsidies to renewables.</p><p>While it is near impossible to disentangle the social or environmental impact of this, my own reading suggests that precious little of it has materially aided either the poor or the planet. Like so many attempts to distort markets for benign reasons, rewards have gone to landowners, contractors, consultants and power companies, impeding growth by driving up prices to consumers.</p><p>The government is right at least to start with competition. Breaking the big six oligopoly must be right. But a deep audit of energy policy, its subsidies and market corruption is desperately needed. Otherwise none of us will know where to begin.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421104994|2013-11-05T11:03:55Z|4d2e6631fe1f9f197c03fb0e5abab32fb18545d3 -->",
