      "id":"politics/2013/oct/29/energy-companies-heartwarming",
      "sectionId":"politics",
      "sectionName":"Politics",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-29T22:15:44Z",
      "webTitle":"Energy companies' heartwarming (but not housewarming) performance",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/29/energy-companies-heartwarming",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/politics/2013/oct/29/energy-companies-heartwarming",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"10",
        "trailText":"Listening to the bosses of the energy firms, you'd imagine they were running charities rather than businesses",
        "headline":"Energy companies' heartwarming (but not housewarming) performance",
        "body":"<p>The big energy companies came to account for themselves and their ever rising prices in parliament on Tuesday. It was a heartwarming session. They are so determined to do the right thing, so desperate to be loved by the public, so anxious that, thanks to them, nobody – not the poorest disabled pensioner – will ever have to choose between eating and heating.</p><p>Listening to them, you'd imagine that if anyone phoned in to say they couldn't meet their bill, a top executive would offer to pay it himself – out of his bonus, if necessary. These guys aren't running businesses – they are directing charities.</p><p>You might be sad but not surprised to learn that many MPs on the energy committee did not buy this at face value. Neither did Stephen Fitzpatrick, the MD of the tiny Ovo Energy (0.5% of the market), who sat at the end of the line of witnesses and growled that none of the figures his three colleagues were quoting made any sense to him.</p><p>Gas prices had fallen from 74p a therm in 2011, and his company were buying it for winter at 69p. \"I cannot see any explanation for their prices,\" he said, adding that if they could afford to knock 15% off the bills of customers who had quit (it is called a \"winback deduction\") they could afford to do it for everyone. People would ask, if they could pay all that back now, how long had they been overcharging?</p><p>The other three, from much bigger companies, looked askance. (I am not certain what \"askance\" means, but I know that's what they were looking.) I haven't seen such a look, combining contempt with, as we say here, a complete ignoral – at least not since Jeffrey Archer had to share an Old Bailey dock with the man who had shopped him to the police.</p><p>They must also have been deeply resentful of the way Mr Fitzpatrick was getting stacks of free publicity for his company. A colleague tells me that, in fact, Ovo would cost him £172 more per year than npower, but he's on npower's lowest tariff. If everyone on npower's eye-watering top tariff were to switch, the lowest charges would shoot up. It's very, very complicated.</p><p>William Morris, of SSE (8.2% price rise), said movingly that nobody should be in a position where they had to choose between eating and heating. There would be help. \"We don't want to fuel their fears,\" he said. Of course not. They can't afford to fuel anything at those prices!</p><p>It was all a problem of publicity. The public, and I paraphrase, had no idea what wonderful people the energy companies were. \"We have to get that message across!\" he said. Why, they had 20,000 employees who needed to be paid. \"They are equally members of society,\" he said gravely, and we had a vision of power workers shivering in the dark, purely to keep down the bills of selfish, rapacious customers.</p><p>The gist of their argument was that the government should pay. At the moment energy prices are like the poll tax, the same for everyone. Fund it out of taxation, and you could cut bills. So – again I paraphrase – we could all pay less to the energy companies if we paid more to the energy companies.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421240722|2013-11-05T11:03:55Z|44845f06d4210df153be4355c566644558cd2202 -->",
