        "trailText":"The big six energy companies are due to face MPs over rising prices",
        "headline":"Business blog: Energy bosses defend price hikes - as it happened",
        "body":"<div id=\"block-5270053fe4b0ffc73763b671\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T19:09:53.256Z\">7.09pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Closing summary</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>We will have to wait another day to hear full evidence from Andrew Wright at Ofgem, who is asked to come back later.&nbsp;</p> <p>Quick summary: Energy bosses defended their price increases and argued for green levies to be moved off customers' bills and into general taxation.</p> <p><strong>Tony Cocker of E.ON</strong> said he had called on the prime minister to launch a competition investigation.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>I fundamentally believe that this market is competitive but I acknowledge we are not trusted and therefore I believe we need to have a very thorough competition commission investigation.</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>Andrew Wright</strong> of<strong> Ofgem </strong>said the regulator had launched &quot;the most significant reforms&quot; since competition was introduced.</p> <p><strong>John Robertson </strong>for<strong> Labour&nbsp;</strong>accused the companies of failing to protect their most vulnerable customers.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>There are thousands of people dying because of government policy... and the big reason is they die of hypothermia because they can't afford to put the heating on.</p> <p>To just say you move them on to prepayment because they cannot afford to protect their bills, sorry, you need to do more to protect them.</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>That's all from me today. Thank you for following and join us tomorrow for more rolling news on the Guardian business blog.</strong></p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T19:10:09.308Z\">at 7.10pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526ffe82e4b0ffc73763b66c\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T18:35:24.679Z\">6.35pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Over on the <strong>Spectator</strong>'s Coffee House <a href=\"http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/coffeehouse/2013/10/energy-bosses-boost-tory-tortoise-in-energy-row-with-green-taxes-pledge/\">blog</a>, <strong>Isabel Hardman</strong> sounds underwhelmed by MPs' performance in taking on the energy bosses: &quot;the energy companies have hardly had the grilling they were expecting: more of a gentle warming.&quot;</p> <p>She writes that&nbsp;the person who has done the most to make the big six witnesses uncomfortable is one of the other witnesses: Stephen Fitzpatrick, the managing director of Ovo Energy.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>He took apart those sitting next to him in the Thatcher Room, saying that Ovo couldn’t see the prices on the wholesale market that would lead to the sort of rises that the Big Six have been announcing recently.&nbsp;</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>John Rentoul</strong> at the<strong> Independent</strong> also thinks that the MPs failed to inflict &quot;<a href=\"http://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/the-big-six-in-front-of-mps-this-was-supposed-to-be-a-grilling-but-even-russell-brand-would-have-struggled-to-give-one-8911552.html\">ritual cathartic humiliation</a>&quot;.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Normal people don’t have to sit through select committee meetings, but I suspect that most of us have an understanding of market economics that works at two levels. Level one is that prices seem to go up a lot, don’t seem to go down when world prices go down, and that the bosses of a lot of companies seem to get paid an awful lot, which doesn’t seem to go down if their companies do badly. But level two is that nationalising the energy industry would not make gas and electricity bills magically cheaper.</p> </blockquote> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T18:45:39.236Z\">at 6.45pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526ffa97e4b08c7e086ff154\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T18:26:54.237Z\">6.26pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Still waiting for MPs to return to the Thatcher room to wrap up this session on the 'big six' with Ofgem's chief executive.</p> <p>So time for a quick backgrounder: earlier this year the committee accused Ofgem of failing to improve transparency in the energy market. Ofgem hired BDO accountancy firm to advise on financial reporting of energy companies, but then failed to take up its recommendations, arguing they would put unnecessary burdens on the big six.</p> <p>MPs rejected this argument in their <a href=\"http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmselect/cmenergy/108/10802.htm\">report on energy prices, profits and poverty</a>:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>We believe that taken as a whole, the benefits of BDOs recommendations - in terms of improvements to transparency and comparability of the statements and associated improvements in consumer trust - significantly outweigh any burdens on the six largest vertically integrated energy companies.&nbsp;</p> <p>We recommend that Ofgem should require the six largest vertically integrated companies to implement BDO' recommendations 1 (publishing statements to the same year-end), 2 (independent auditor opinion on statements), and 4(reporting of trading function results). We also encourage Ofgem to consider requiring implementation of BDO's recommendations in full and to publish, in its response to this report, its analysis of the cost to energy companies of full implementation.&nbsp;</p> </blockquote> <p>With MPs calling Ofgem &quot;a paper tiger&quot;, it is not only the big six energy bosses that are attempting to defend their reputations today.&nbsp;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526ff809e4b0ded76c0a9112\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T18:02:00.671Z\">6.02pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The division bell is ringing again. Short break while MPs go off to vote.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526ff71ce4b0ffc73763b662\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T18:01:41.986Z\">6.01pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Alan Whitehead is asking about the BDO recommendations (see<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/29/business-blog-india-raises-interest-rates-to-tackle-inflation-live#block-526fdd0ae4b01566f5a3942e\"> 4.08</a> for background).</p> <p>Wright says Ofgem has committed to looking again at those recommendations and will be coming out with a call for evidence and &quot;engaging with stakeholders&quot;.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>We have led the way in improving transparency in this market.. without the actions we took this debate would not be possible.</p> </blockquote> <p>This should be seen as Ofgem's defence, after the same group of MPs criticised the regulator for dismissing the BDO report, a series of recommendations to improve transparency.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526ff642e4b0ffc73763b660\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:56:51.764Z\">5.56pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>One MP thinks a different energy market model could work better: why not have &quot;fierce competition&quot; in generating electricity, but have co-operatively owned business model to supply consumers.</p> <p>Wright says there are many different models of running energy systems throughout the world. &quot;It is the government's policy to have a competitive market in the supply of retail and gas.&quot;</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:57:27.871Z\">at 5.57pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526ff5b4e4b0ffc73763b65e\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:53:04.946Z\">5.53pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Sounding non specific (to my ears), Wright says the regulator has a range of powers to ensure the market is working properly.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526ff57be4b0ffc73763b65d\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:51:16.574Z\">5.51pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Andrew Wright says the regulator is introducing the &quot;most significant reforms&quot; since competition was introduced that will make a real difference to consumers and suppliers.&nbsp;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526ff528e4b0ded76c0a910f\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:50:43.958Z\">5.50pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Worth a quick reminder that earlier this year the committee criticised Ofgem for not doing enough to ensure companies were open and transparent.&nbsp;You can read the full report <a href=\"http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmselect/cmenergy/108/10802.htm\">here</a>.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526ff4c0e4b0ffc73763b65c\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:48:56.298Z\">5.48pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Now in the final session MPs are quizzing&nbsp;Andrew Wright, the interim chief executive officer of regulator Ofgem.</p> <p>He starts by promising an annual review of market competition starting next spring.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526ff48ce4b0ffc73763b65b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:47:21.158Z\">5.47pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>And on that note, part two is over, with the feed cutting our abruptly...</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526ff42de4b0ffc73763b65a\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:46:35.944Z\">5.46pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Ian Peters confirms to Labour MP Ian Lavery that British Gas made &pound;1.08 bn pre tax profits last year.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526ff367e4b0ded76c0a910d\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:44:41.071Z\">5.44pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>John Robertson (Lab) accuses the companies of not doing enough to protect people in fuel poverty.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>There are thousands of people dying because of government policy... and the big reason is they die of hypothermia because they can't afford to put the heating on.</p> <p>To just say you move them on to prepayment because they cannot afford to protect their bills, sorry you need to do more to protect them.</p> </blockquote> <p>The executives all say they will do more...</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526ff2b5e4b0ded76c0a910c\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:41:52.890Z\">5.41pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>John Robertson is asking about &quot;excessive&quot; charges for sending out letters and disconnecting customers.</p> <p>He says when indebted customers are moved onto prepayment metres, they are being &quot;disconnected by the back door&quot;.</p> <p>Ian Peters of British Gas says it is a responsible way for these customers to repay debts. He claims British Gas is the only energy company checking to make sure these customers are not cut off.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526ff227e4b0ffc73763b658\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:38:32.962Z\">5.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Martin Lawrence says EDF<strong> hasn't made its mind up yet</strong> on whether it plans to raise prices.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526ff107e4b0ded76c0a910a\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:35:07.588Z\">5.35pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Ramsay Dunning of Co-operative Energy, says the energy sector has a perception problem. It looks like an oligopoly. He doesn't think it is, but argues that potential new market entrants are deterred by lack of market transparency.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>I am not asking for the breakup of the big six, but we need to do something to change that appearance.</p> </blockquote> <p>He argues that power generation and retail supply of energy to households should be split. This &quot;vertical integration&quot; feeds the perception of an uncompetitive industry.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526ff088e4b0ded76c0a9109\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:31:48.534Z\">5.31pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Alan Whitehead, Labour, wants to know why 'big six' energy company price rises march in step. Ian Peters of British Gas says 2013 is an unusual year, partly because of the introduction of the eco-levy.&nbsp;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fee97e4b01566f5a3943b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:24:13.446Z\">5.24pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Neil Clitheroe of Scottish Power takes up the eco levy tax argument, saying the UK is one of the few countries that puts the charge on bills. &quot;If that separate people we could reference that point straight away and say that's what we pay.&quot;&nbsp;</p> <p><em>JR -This is emerging as the line-to-take for the energy companies today.</em></p> <p>Martin Lawrence of EDF chips in, asking for more stability and clarity about the future of the green levy.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:24:44.907Z\">at 5.24pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526fee0de4b0ffc73763b652\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:20:27.049Z\">5.20pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Now Ian Peters of British Gas argues that the eco levy should be shifted into general taxation, rather than put on customers' bills.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fed8ee4b0ffc73763b651\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:18:22.792Z\">5.18pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Christopher Pincher (Conservative), citing research from the Institute of Public Policy Research, says that 1/3 of British Gas price hike could be avoided if they delivered on energy efficiency. Peters says he doesn't understand where that analysis comes from.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:18:35.693Z\">at 5.18pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526fecc1e4b08c7e086ff14f\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T17:14:32.065Z\">5.14pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Ian Peters of British Gas says 1% of the fall in customers' energy use is not related to energy efficiency measures, suggesting this could be related to changing habits.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fec3ee4b01566f5a3943a\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time