ergy bosses are saying nobody gets cut off.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T15:42:48.463Z\">at 3.42pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526fd65de4b08c7e086ff143\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T15:41:09.802Z\">3.41pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Robertson is still unhappy about the lack of transparency over big six profits.</p> <p>&nbsp;According to Ofgem, energy companies make 23% profit on generating electricity while their own figures suggest profits 17-23%, he says. Yet these profits are not taken into account by their retail arms, when companies raise consumers' bills. Why?</p> <p>How can shareholders get dividends on 20% energy generation profits, while consumers get 10% increases in their energy bills he asks.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fd61be4b01566f5a39428\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T15:37:45.688Z\">3.37pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Guy Johnson of nPower says the firm has taken &pound;170m in subsidies for renewable energy in the last few years, &quot;vastly dwarfed by the &pound;2.3bn we have invested&quot;.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fd561e4b01566f5a39426\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T15:36:41.231Z\">3.36pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>John Robertson (Labour) wants to know where these companies are paying taxes.</p> <p>Tony Cocker of E.On replies:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>I assume therefore that the German company pays German taxes and the British company pays British taxes.</p> </blockquote> <p>Robertson</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>I would expect a CEO to know...</p> </blockquote> <p>Cocker</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>We pay taxes here in the UK and we are proud to pay taxes in the UK...</p> </blockquote> <p>Robertson</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>You are not trying hard enough...</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fd4d3e4b08c7e086ff141\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T15:33:40.392Z\">3.33pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>John Robertson for Labour gets to the heart of the matter:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Do you understand that the people in this country do not trust you? How do you expect to get that trust back?</p> </blockquote> <p>William Morris (NPower) says 15 months ago he was one of those people. He is a newcomer to the energy industry.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>We have a profound problem on our hands.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fd3f2e4b08c7e086ff140\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T15:31:07.927Z\">3.31pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Albert Owen, Labour, is also asking about the eco levies, pointing out they were only introduced in April.</p> <p>&quot;Many of my constituents don't have the luxury of those discounts because they don't have a dual-fuel bill,&quot; he adds. So why should they have to pay more?</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fd348e4b0ffc73763b63c\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T15:27:20.537Z\">3.27pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>If the green levies are lifted will you pass on the saving to your customers, asks Pincher (Con) referring to David Cameron's pledge to roll back green levies.</p> <p>&quot;Unquestionably yes,&quot; says Johnson of nPower. &quot;Pound for pound, penny for penny, that should come straight off the customer's bill.&quot;</p> <p>Tony Cocker of E.ON is not giving a yes or no answer.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fd29de4b08c7e086ff13f\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T15:24:18.137Z\">3.24pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Christopher Pincher, a Conservative member of the committee, is asking nPower's Guy Johnson why their eco levy costs are higher than their competitors.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>We will do absolutely everything in our interest to deliver them as efficiently as possible.</p> </blockquote> <p>Johnson says fuel poverty is profoundly worrying for him. &quot;We don't want anybody to be in that situation.&quot;</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T15:24:37.751Z\">at 3.24pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526fd1d0e4b01566f5a39425\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T15:21:02.659Z\">3.21pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Back onto the eco levies, Guy Johnson of nPower says the scheme add up to &pound;60 on the bill.&nbsp;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fd0d4e4b0ded76c0a90f9\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T15:17:25.392Z\">3.17pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Tony Cocker of E.ON, which has not yet raised its prices, says the firm has not yet decided if it will raise its prices. &quot;We will hold our prices as long as we can.&quot;</p> <p>This doesn't impress the committee - one MP says &quot;it means nothing &quot;.</p> <p>Cocker blames the green levies, describing them as &quot;a regressive poll tax&quot;.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fcfc1e4b0ded76c0a90f5\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T15:14:20.153Z\">3.14pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Barry Gardiner, a Labour member of the committee, is going after the companies on their price rises, and why despite different strategies they all put up their prices at the same time.</p> <p>William Morris of SSE counters &quot;things are changing&quot;. He says the firm has made a loss of &pound;21m.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fceb0e4b0ffc73763b637\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T15:06:54.642Z\">3.06pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Tony Cocker claims E.ON has invested &pound;7bn in the last five years. &quot;There is some misinformation that investment has stalled in the last five years, that isn't what I am hearing.&quot;</p> <p>He goes on to claim they have invested 100% of what they have earned in the last 5 years.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fce3ce4b0ffc73763b636\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T15:04:42.778Z\">3.04pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Stephen Fitzpatrick of Ovo Energy says in January 2012 they were the first energy company to announce a price cut. Although it is worth pointing out this cut was wiped out in the following April with a price rise of 5.8%...</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fcd7ee4b08c7e086ff13d\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T15:02:42.389Z\">3.02pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Guy Johnson of nPower is being quizzed about profits and whether UK profits are being fed back to the home company. nPower is owned by German utility RWE. He insists &quot;there is no old fashioned transfer pricing going on&quot;, but acknowledges&nbsp;&quot;an element of concern and suspicion.. that there are excess profits&quot;.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fcbe8e4b01566f5a39423\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T14:59:47.512Z\">2.59pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Tony Cocker of E.ON denies the charge that companies are subsidising their retail business.&nbsp;He says his business is very transparent.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fcb49e4b08c7e086ff13c\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T14:53:23.093Z\">2.53pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Stephen Fitzpatrick continues his attack on the big six: &quot;A significant number of the big six are charging the maximum they can get away with.&quot;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fc9ffe4b08c7e086ff13a\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T14:50:24.986Z\">2.50pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Now up Stephen Fitzpatrick from energy minnow Ovo Energy, based in Bristol with 140,000 customers.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>I cannot explain any of these prices rises. They are not the prices we see in the liquid wholesale market.</p> <p>Like some of the committee members I have been somewhat confused looking at the explanations for some of the price rises.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fc89ee4b01566f5a39420\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T14:43:37.674Z\">2.43pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Morris of SSE is getting grilled over the breakdown of SSE's costs.</p> <p>The wholesale energy proportion of the bill is half the bill, another large proportion is transporting energy, the cost of social and environmental schemes account for 10% of bills and have gone up 13%.</p> <p>&quot;We would like to see those costs off customer bills and coming out of taxation.&quot; He says he is paying the same proportion of his income on these levies as someone living in fuel poverty, which &quot;clearly isn't morally defensible&quot;.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fc80de4b08c7e086ff139\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T14:38:24.815Z\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>William Morris of SSE says that OFGEM have revised their position and says company &quot;regrets profoundly&quot; having to put up prices. &quot;None of us want prices to rise.&quot;</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fc7c6e4b01566f5a3941f\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T14:36:36.220Z\">2.36pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>First question is on prices, how can they be explained when Ofgem says wholesale prices have only risen by 1.7%?</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fc79ae4b01566f5a3941e\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T14:35:39.110Z\">2.35pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>We are getting started... introductions from E.ON, SSE, NPower and Ovo Energy</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fc603e4b0ded76c0a90f3\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T14:31:31.116Z\">2.31pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Some background reading:</p> <p>The BBC has put together this handy <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-24670741?print=true\">explainer on the Big Six</a></p> <p>The Guardian's energy editor Terry Macalister&nbsp;has set out <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/27/questions-big-six-energy-firms-must-answer-prices\">5 questions they must </a><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/27/questions-big-six-energy-firms-must-answer-prices\">answer</a>.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fc535e4b0ffc73763b633\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T14:27:55.328Z\">2.27pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Here is a full run down of the <a href=\"http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/energy-and-climate-change-committee/news/energy-prices/\">agenda</a>. As my colleague Jill Treanor has pointed out, it's worth noting that <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/blog/2013/oct/28/energy-firms-mps-eon-chief-executive\">only E.ON have bothered to put up their UK chief executive</a>.</p> <p>Panel 1 at 2.30pm</p> <ul> <li> <p>Tony Cocker, Chief Executive Officer, E.ON</p> </li> <li> <p>William Morris, Managing Director, SSE</p> </li> <li> <p>Guy Johnson, External Affairs Director, RWEnpower</p> </li> <li> <p>Stephen Fitzpatrick, Managing Director, Ovo Energy</p> </li> </ul> <p>Panel 2 at 3.30pm</p> <ul> <li> <p>Neil Clitheroe, Chief Executive Officer - Retail and Generation, ScottishPower</p> </li> <li> <p>Ian Peters, Managing Director - Energy, British Gas</p> </li> <li> <p>Martin Lawrence, Managing Director - Energy Sourcing and Customer Supply, EDF Energy</p> </li> <li> <p>Ramsay Dunning, Group General Manager, Co-operative Energy</p> </li> </ul> <p>Panel 3 at 4.30pm</p> <ul> <li>Andrew Wright, Interim Chief Executive Officer, Ofgem</li> </ul> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fc467e4b08c7e086ff137\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T14:23:04.335Z\">2.23pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Interest in the select committee hearing seems to be huge.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/jessbrammar/statuses/395188069055598592\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Overheard in queue to watch select committee: &quot;oh, everyone's here to see kicking of the energy companies...&quot;.No sign of popcorn sellers yet</p>— Jess Brammar (@jessbrammar) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/jessbrammar/statuses/395188069055598592\">October 29, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/jessbrammar/statuses/395187036396986368\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Large queue of interested members of public forming outside Portcullis House for appearance of Big Six energy companies at select ctte...</p>— Jess Brammar (@jessbrammar) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/jessbrammar/statuses/395187036396986368\">October 29, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fc27fe4b0ffc73763b630\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T14:18:18.130Z\">2.18pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Energy bosses to face MPs over price rises</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Hi Jennifer Rankin taking over from Angela Monaghan.</p> <p>Now moving to one of the most keenly-anticipated event of the day. Energy bosses from the ‘big six’ energy companies, will shortly appear before the energy and climate change select committee. Energy chief executives are about as popular as bankers, so this should be a charged session.</p> <p>A quick recap: Sir Robert Smith, the Lib Dem chair of the committee, asked the energy companies to appear last week after a wave of price increase.</p> <p>NPower, British Gas, SSE and Scottish Power have all said they will increase electricity and gas prices by between 8% and 10.4% while Eon and EDF are expected to follow suit.</p> <p>The increases will take the cost of an average dual-fuel bill to more than &pound;1,400 a year.</p> <p>You can follow the session starting at 2.30 <a href=\"http://www.parliamentlive.tv/Main/Player.aspx?meetingId=14057\">here</a></p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fbf64e4b0ffc73763b62f\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T14:04:40.327Z\">2.04pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">US consumer confidence falls more sharply than expected</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/CVecchioFX/statuses/395188334886019073\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Huge drop in US Consumer Confidence, 71.2 from 79.7</p>— Christopher Vecchio (@CVecchioFX) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/CVecchioFX/statuses/395188334886019073\">October 29, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>US consumer confidence dropped to 71.2 on the Conference Board's October index, from 80.2 in September (revised from 79.7). Economists had forecast a much more modest fall to 75.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T14:08:35.991Z\">at 2.08pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526fb868e4b0ffc73763b62e\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T13:57:51.719Z\">1.57pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">US markets open higher</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>US markets have opened up:</p> <p><strong>Dow Jones</strong>: +0.32% at 15,618.58</p> <p><strong>S&amp;P 500</strong>: +0.27% at 1,766.90</p> <p><strong>Nasdaq</strong>: +0.05% at 3,384.39</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526fb324e4b0ded76c0a90ed\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T13:30:14.823Z\">1.30pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">US retail sales fall 0.1% in September</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-453ce8fa-1a7a-4a82-a443-0d23ddedde2f\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/29/1383054557870/216b26af-6bc5-448b-a59c-e3d04f292fcb-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"US retail sales fell 0.1% in September.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>US retail sales fell 0.1% in September. Photograph: Robert Harding World Imagery/A/Alamy</figcaption> </figure> <p>Weak car sales were a drag in September, pushing overall <a href=\"http://www.census.gov/retail/\">retail sales down 0.1%</a> on a monthly basis. It wasn't far off economists' prediction of flat sales.</p> <p>Excluding cars, retail sales actually rose by a 0.4%, and sales were 3.2% higher compared with September 2012.</p> <p>Economists said it was difficult to get too excited about the numbers because they related to the period before the US government shutdown.&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>James Knightley</strong> of ING said:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>We have to remember that this was a pre-government shutdown figure and so its usefulness as a guide for Federal Reserve policy is limited.</p> </blockquote> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T13:49:39.795Z\">at 1.49pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526fad54e4b08c7e086ff130\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T12:50:32.104Z\">12.50pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">European shares - lunchtime round-up</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Europe's major indices are still higher.</p> <p><strong>FTSE 100</strong>: +0.61% at 6,766.38</p> <p><strong>CAC 40</strong>: +0.5% at 4,272.78</p> <p><strong>DAX 30</strong>: +0.18% at 8,995.09</p> <p><strong>IBEX</strong>: +1.11% at 9,844.6</p> <p><strong>FTSE MIB</strong>: +1.75% at 19,158</p> <p>London traders returned to their desks today after Britain's <a href=\"http://www.guprod.gnl/uk-news/2013/oct/29/storm-death-destruction-return-to-work\">worst storm in a decade</a>. While travel was severely disrupted and hundreds of thosands of homes lost power, economics editor <strong>Larry Elliot</strong> believes the economic impact will be limted.</p> <p>He <a href=\"http://www.guprod.gnl/business/economics-blog/2013/oct/28/storm-battered-britain-not-economy-bad-weather\">argues</a>:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>There are good reasons for expecting Britain's growth rate to slow down as 2013 draws to a close but the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/oct/28/britain-storm-winds-death-flooding\">storm that has battered the south of England </a>is not one of them.</p> <p>To be sure, a complete shutdown of the country would have an impact on national output, as was illustrated by the blizzards in December 2010.</p> <p>They had a material impact on gross domestic product in the fourth quarter of that year because the disruption was widespread and protracted.</p> <p>But that's not going to be the case this time. Firstly, the storm passed quickly and the Met Office gave plenty of warning that the bad <a href=\"http://www.guprod.gnl/uk/weather\">weather</a> was coming so people planned to work from home. Secondly, many workers were off anyway because of school half-term holidays. Thirdly, many of those who had an unexpected day off will have spent money in shops and restaurants. Finally, the fact that the bad weather came in October – the first month of the fourth quarter of 2013 – means there will be plenty of time to make up for lost output.</p> <p>There will have been some loss of output as a result of the bad weather, but at the most it will have shaved 0.1 points off GDP in the fourth quarter, and probably less than that.</p> </blockquote> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T12:58:34.652Z\">at 12.58pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526fac59e4b0ffc73763b627\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T12:42:38.366Z\">12.42pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">More on UK mortgages...</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Katie Allen</strong>, the Guardian's economics reporter, tells how the biggest rise in UK mortgage approvals since February 2008 is &quot;fanning fears&quot; of a fresh housing market bubble:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/mortgages\">Mortgages</a> approved by British lenders jumped to their highest level for more than five years in September, fanning fears the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/housingmarket\">housing market</a> was already heating up even before the latest government support kicked in.</p> <p>Banks, building societies and other lenders <a href=\"http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/statistics/documents/mc/2013/sep/tablesa-n.xlsx\">approved 66,735 mortgages in September</a>, the biggest monthly total since February 2008, before the global financial crisis took hold.</p> <p>The figures, from the <a href=\"http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/statistics/Pages/mc/2013/sep/default.aspx\">Bank of England</a>, were just ahead of City forecasts for 66,000 and compared with an upwardly revised 63,396 in August. Mortgage approvals are seen by economists as a good early indicator of where the housing market is headed.</p> <p>They follow government data on Monday showing <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/28/house-prices-rise-england-land-registry-bubble\">house prices rose in every English region in September</a> and are likely to be seized on by those who argue that the government's <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/help-to-buy-scheme\">Help to Buy scheme</a> risks creating a new bubble.</p> </blockquote> <p>Read the full story <strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/29/mortgage-approvals-february-2008-help-to-buy\">here</a></strong>.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526f9d5ce4b08c7e086ff12f\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T11:48:38.194Z\">11.48am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Ireland gets a final visit from Troika of international lenders</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-f7f32f83-cc24-4f43-9c8e-9c09f015366d\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/2/29/1330519545721/An-Irish-flag-flies-next--008.jpg\" alt=\"Ireland to receive a final visit from the Troika of international lenders.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Ireland to receive a final visit from the Troika of international lenders. Photograph: Francois Lenoir/Reuters</figcaption> </figure> <p>Lenders from the International Monetary Fund, European Union, and European Central Bank - the so-called <strong>Troika</strong> - will pay a final visit to Dublin today.</p> <p>It follows the bailout which Ireland was forced into following the near collapse of its banking system at the height of the financial crisis. The country is hoping to become the first to exit the rescue programme.</p> <p>This from our Ireland correspondent <strong>Henry McDonald</strong>, in Dublin:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Officials from the International Monetary Fund, the EU and the European Bank will make their 12th and final visit to the Irish capital today to review the Republic's economy as heads towards exiting the bail out.</p> <p>The so-called Troika will examine the progress Ireland is making towards driving down its national debt and moving to restoring economic sovereignty.</p> <p>Ireland will become the first country in the EU to leave the bail out programme.</p> <p>The Republic was forced to borrow 67.5bn euros (&pound;57.4bn) after its biggest banks almost collapsed in November 2010.</p> <p>However, the state's debt-to-GDP ratio is still around 120% and Irish banks have yet to properly deal with the tens of thousands of its customers in mortgage arrears. Meanwhile, unemployment remains more than 14 per cent of the workforce.</p> </blockquote> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T11:54:24.463Z\">at 11.54am GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526f99a1e4b08c7e086ff12e\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T11:25:09.331Z\">11.25am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Former Co-op bosses grilled by MPs</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Our City Editor <strong>Jill Treanor</strong> is following the session live and tweeting <strong><a href=\"https://twitter.com/jilltreanor\">here</a></strong>.</p> <p><strong>Barry Tootell</strong>, former chief executive of the bank, has told MPs that the downgrade to junk status by Moody's in May was more severe than expected. He has also denied misleading the market about the state of the bank.</p> <p>See <strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/27/co-operative-group-retail?CMP=twt_gu\">here</a></strong> for a great read on the Co-op fiasco.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/jilltreanor/statuses/395155911557148672\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Barry Tootell says it was his recommendation that the Verde deal - the Lloyds branches - should not proceed</p>— Jill Treanor (@jilltreanor) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/jilltreanor/statuses/395155911557148672\">October 29, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T11:58:43.766Z\">at 11.58am GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526f943ce4b08c7e086ff12c\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T11:09:06.244Z\">11.09am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Spanish retail sales rise for the first time in more than three years</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Turning to Spain, retail sales rose by 2.2% in September compared with the same month a year earlier. It followed a 4.8% drop in August according to official figures, and marked the first annual rise in more than three years.</p> <p><strong>Chris Williamson</strong>, chief economist at <strong>Markit</strong>, puts the rise into context on Twitter:</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/WilliamsonChris/statuses/395133254967119873\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Retail sales in <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Spain&amp;src=hash\">#Spain</a> charted: 1st annual rise (+2.2%) since Jun'10. Have been only 4 +ve y/y sales months since2007 <a href=\"http://t.co/raflkzAMp2\">pic.twitter.com/raflkzAMp2</a></p>— Chris Williamson (@WilliamsonChris) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/WilliamsonChris/statuses/395133254967119873\">October 29, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-526f8b1fe4b0ffc73763b61b\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T10:28:50.248Z\">10.28am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">UK mortgage approvals highest in more than five and a half years</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-d02bef88-7bfb-420e-946f-8926aa7f1cff\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Money/Pix/pictures/2009/12/23/1261565871131/Mortgage-approvals-increa-001.jpg\" alt=\"Mortgage approvals increased by 5.3% in September\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Mortgage approvals increased by 5.3% in September to the highest level in more than five and a half years. Photograph: Russell Boyce/Reuters</figcaption> </figure> <p><strong>UK mortgage approvals</strong> for house purchases (i.e. excluding remortgages) rose 5.3% to 66,735 in September, from 63,396 in August.</p> <p>It was the highest level since February 2008, before the global financial crisis intensified in September that year with the collapse of US investment bank <strong>Lehman Brothers</strong>.</p> <p>The <strong>Bank of England</strong> data will be taken as a further sign that Britain's housing market was warming up even before the second phase of the government's <strong>Help to Buy</strong> scheme was introduced earlier this month. However, mortgage approvals are still below pre-crisis levels, with monthly approvals averaging above 100,000 in 2006 and 2007.</p> <p><strong>Howard Archer</strong>, chief UK economist at<strong> IHS Global Insight</strong>, had this to say on the Bank's data:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The marked increase in mortgage approvals in September provides compelling evidence that housing market activity was already gaining appreciable momentum even before the Help to Buy mortgage guarantee scheme came into being in early October.</p> <p>While the strength of house price rises in London is becoming an increasing concern and pushing up the overall national increase in house prices, we are currently a long way off from an overall housing market bubble emerging.</p> <p>Nevertheless, there is a mounting danger that house prices could really take off over the coming months, especially ifalready significantly improving housing market activity and rising buyer interest is lifted appreciably further by the Help to Buy mortgage guarantee scheme</p> <p>It is therefore of vital importance that policymakers closely monitor the situation and are prepared to act quickly and decisively if signs of the housing market overheating become increasingly widespread and pronounced.</p> </blockquote> <p>The <strong>Bank of England</strong> also revealed that lending to non-financial companies&nbsp;rose by &pound;720m in September., following a &pound;3.7m fall in August.</p> <p>However, while lending to large companies increased by &pound;1.1bn, loans to small and medium-sized enterprises fell by &pound;383m. </p> <p><strong>Adam Marshall,</strong> director of policy and external affairs at the<strong> British Chambers of Commerce</strong>, said more help was needed for SMEs:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>It’s good to see overall business lending rise, as this has an impact on business confidence. Yet these new figures show that while large firms have little difficulty tapping debt markets, SMEs – and particular young, fast-growing firms – continue to struggle to access growth capital.</p> <p>Both policy-makers and financial institutions need to do more to help fast-growing SMEs access finance. The British Business Bank has a huge role to play here, and should be enhanced with additional capital to help plug the gap.</p> </blockquote> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T13:42:49.868Z\">at 1.42pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526f8169e4b0ffc73763b618\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T09:47:50.222Z\">9.47am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">European markets are up</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The major European markets are all slightly higher this morning:</p> <p><strong>FTSE 100</strong>: +0.36% at 6,749.05</p> <p><strong>CAC 40</strong>: +0.17% at 4,258.99</p> <p><strong>DAX 30</strong>: +0.07% at 8,985.04</p> <p><strong>IBEX</strong>: +0.55% at 9,789.2</p> <p><strong>FTSE MIB</strong>: +1.3% at 19,073.95</p> <p><strong>BP</strong> is the biggest riser on the <strong>FTSE 100</strong>, with shares up 5% at 475p.</p> <p>The company is flying high after a better than expected set of third-quarter results which included a dividend hike and a plegde to return proceeds of asset sales to shareholders. It plans to sell $10bn (&pound;6.2bn) of assets by the end of 2015. </p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T09:59:47.530Z\">at 9.59am GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526f77d6e4b0ded76c0a90d6\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T09:12:15.639Z\">9.12am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">MPs to grill Big Six energy providers</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-8cd33c77-6212-4bbf-aa33-003b6f1b8bb3\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/29/1383039260326/a2851f7c-9dfa-412e-a6a2-ae65deda565e-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Britain's Big Six energy providers will be grilled by MPs this afternoon on recent price rises.  EPA/ANDY RAIN\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Britain's Big Six energy providers will be grilled by MPs this afternoon on recent price rises. EPA/ANDY RAIN Photograph: ANDY RAIN/EPA</figcaption> </figure> <p>MPs on House of Commons select committees are in for a busy day. The main event starts at 2.30 in the Thatcher Room, Portcullis House, when the <strong>Big Six energy companies</strong> will be grilled on prices by the <strong>energy and climate change committee</strong>.</p> <p>I think they can expect some fairly robust questioning following the intense debate about rising UK energy bills. First we had Labour <strong>Ed Miliband</strong>, who pledged to freeze energy prices for 20 months should his party be elected at the next election.</p> <p>Then came the prices rises. Four of the Big Six - <strong>SSE</strong>, <strong>British Gas</strong>, <strong>npower</strong> and <strong>Scottish Power</strong> - moved in quick succession, with some customers facing price hikes of more than 10% just in time for winter.</p> <p>MPs will no doubt try to get to the bottom of what is really happening to wholesale energy prices, and how they affect household bills.</p> <p>As <strong>Rowena Mason</strong>, The Guardian's political correspondent, reports:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Some of Britain's big six energy companies have seen their wholesale electricity costs fall over the last three years while still putting up prices for millions of households.</p> <p>The figures will put yet more pressure on the firms to explain why bills and UK profits have been going up, as they appear before a influential House of Commons committee of MPs.</p> </blockquote> <p>Read the full story <strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/29/energy-firms-raised-prices-as-wholesale-costs-fall\">here</a></strong>.</p> <p>Other promising sessions today:</p> <p><strong>9.30am - </strong>Business, Innovation and Skills Committee takes evidence on the <strong>UK retail sector</strong> from witnesses including veteran retailer <strong>Bill Grimse</strong>y and business minister <strong>Michael Fallon</strong>.</p> <p><strong>10am</strong> - Treasury Committee takes evidence from former executives of the <strong>Co-operative Banking Group </strong>on the collapse of the deal to buy more than 600 Lloyds branches, know as Project Verde.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T09:43:22.594Z\">at 9.43am GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526f6bb4e4b0ffc73763b617\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T08:11:08.926Z\">8.11am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Britain's banks are the biggest fallers this morning</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Banks are not popular this morning. The <strong>FTSE 100</strong> has opened slightly higher, up 0.2% at 6,740, but <strong>UK banks</strong> are trading lower.</p> <p>Lloyds Banking Group: -3.3% at 77<br />Royal Bank of Scotland: -2% at 360.2<br />Standard Chartered: -1.8% at 1,506<br />Barclays: -1.1% at 260.4</p> <p><strong>Lloyds</strong> has this morning revealed a further &pound;750m hit for payment protection insurance, taking its total bill for the mis-selling scandal to more than &pound;8bn. The hit contributed to a &pound;440m loss in the third quarter.</p> <p>It was the first update from the bailed out bank since the government started sellling off part of its stake last month.</p> <p>There was some brighter news from Lloyds as chief executive <strong>Ant&oacute;nio Horta-Os&oacute;rio</strong> said it was in discussions to start resuming dividends, and increased his forecasts for margins.</p> <p>Read the full story from our City Editor <strong>Jill Treanor</strong> <strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/29/lloyds-loss-ppi-claims-rise-again\">here</a></strong>.</p> <p>Meanwhile <strong>UBS</strong> shares are down 6% after the Swiss bank was told by regulators that it must increase its capital reserves temporarily by 50% to deal with potential litigation and compliance issues.</p> <p>It dampens the bank's ability's to improve profitability, and hit shares despite a better than expected third-quarter net income of 577 million Swiss francs. Full story <strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/29/ubs-regulators-currency-investigations\">here</a></strong>.</p> <p>Shares in <strong>Deutsche Bank</strong> are down 2.5% after it reported a 94% fall in third quarter profit. It was below expectations and driven partly by a €1.2bn increase in litigation provisions.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/gfhay/statuses/395100064500027392\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Investors have well and truly turned their noses up at bank results today: UBS opens down 5.7%, Lloyds off 3.4%, Deutsche 2.5%.</p>— George Hay (@gfhay) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/gfhay/statuses/395100064500027392\">October 29, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T10:06:05.970Z\">at 10.06am GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-526f68f7e4b0ffc73763b616\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T07:59:25.736Z\">7.59am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">India raises interest rates to 7.75%</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-a8531fab-c28a-4603-86f5-ec42a12319f6\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2013/8/19/1376934171154/The-Reserve-Bank-of-India-010.jpg\" alt=\"The Reserve Bank of India, Mumbai\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) in Mumbai. Photograph: Vivek Prakash/REUTERS</figcaption> </figure> <p><strong>Good morning, and welcome to our rolling coverage of events across the financial market, the global economy, the eurozone and the business world.</strong></p> <p>It's a busy day ahead both on the economics and corporate front in Europe and the US.</p> <p>Overnight India's central bank raised interest rates for a second consecutive month in an attempt to fight inflation and despite sluggish growth.</p> <p>The Reserve Bank of India raised its policy repo rate by 0.25 percentage points to 7.75%. Annual inflation in India rose to 9.84% in September from 9.52% in August. Growth slowed however in the second quarter, to 4.4% on an annual basis.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-10-29T11:18:13.803Z\">at 11.18am GMT</time></p> </div><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421179698|2013-11-05T11:03:55Z|6a82ac2d2c53173f5c514727657ea75dfddaf4b1 -->",
